I was surprised by this wonderful cathedral inÂ PisanÂ RomanesqueÂ style mixed withÂ SieneseÂ influence, discovered in a small town on the hills of Tuscany through Siena and Grosseto. 
Massa Marittima, that had only 527 inhabitant in the year 1737, after the extinction of the Medici dynasty, the Habsburg-Lorraine dynasty took over, which governed the Grand Duchy of Tuscany distinguishing itself for its liberality: while Livorno became one of the most active free ports in the Mediterranean, the Grand Duke Pietro Leopoldo started the agrarian reform and in the years between 1770 and 1790 the areas were reclaimed and in the nineteenth century, through environmental and economic improvement works and Massa returned to being a mining town.
Today Massa Marittima has about 8300 inhabitants and lives mainly on tourism, thanks to the presence of numerous works of art and the enhancement of ancient crafts, mainly related to mines.
